03984nam a22006375i 9780813552224DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135522247 a10.36019/97808135522242doi  a(DE-B1597)529323  a(OCoLC)776108922  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a362.196/8528009732221 aSchuster, David G, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeurasthenic Nation :bAmerica's Search for Health, Happiness, and Comfort, 1869-1920 /cDavid G Schuster. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b14 illustrations and figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Health and Medicine00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Professional Medicine and the Discovery of Neurasthenia -- tChapter 2. The Popular Diagnosis -- tChapter 3. The Search for Inspiration: Neurasthenia and Therapeutic Spirituality -- tChapter 4. Neurasthenia, Health, and Gender -- tChapter 5. Lifestyle and Managing the Healthy Balance -- tChapter 6. The Decline of Neurasthenia -- tEpilogue: Neurasthenia’s Legacy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the United States rushed toward industrial and technological modernization in the late nineteenth century, people worried that the workplace had become too competitive, the economy too turbulent, domestic chores too taxing, while new machines had created a fast-paced environment that sickened the nation. Physicians testified that, without a doubt, modern civilization was causing a host of ills—everything from irritability to insomnia, lethargy to weight loss, anxiety to lack of ambition, and indigestion to impotence. They called this condition neurasthenia. Neurasthenic Nation investigates how the concept of neurasthenia helped doctors and patients, men and women, and advertisers and consumers negotiate changes commonly associated with “modernity.” Combining a survey of medical and popular literature on neurasthenia with original research into rare archives of personal letters, patient records, and corporate files, David Schuster charts the emergence of a “neurasthenic nation”—a place where people saw their personal health as inextricably tied to the pitfalls and possibilities of a changing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355222440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813552224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813552224.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK